First, a bit of background, and then I will explain what I am currently running in Part 2&hellip;
For the last 15 or so years, I have had at least 2 internet connections in to the house&hellip; 2 of them have always been Cable Modems from NTL, which became UPC, and now is Virgin Media. When I started, i think the modems where 150/50kbit/s and 600/150kb/s, and have steadily increased in speed, currently at 360/36Mbit/s each&hellip; But they have always been somewhat separate, and single thread downloads have always been limited to 1 of the connections&hellip; I have been looking for ways around this for years&hellip;
It started with a Linksys RV042 router which allowed me to load balance my connections&hellip; At the time, and i cant even remember when this was, my total bandwidth would not exceed the router. The RV042 has 2 10/100mbit WAN links and 4 100mb/s LAN links&hellip;So, when the connection bandwidth increased, I moved to a new router&hellip;
The next router vendor i tried was Mikrotik. I tried a few different options, including an RB1100 and running their RouterOS on x86 hardware&hellip; Both worked, well, ok, and the Load balancing with nth stuff did do what i needed, along with other stuff, like routing traffic destined for some sites (like BBC iPlayer) to go over a VPN. But in the end, hardware issues and performance problems with the x86 machine (Mikrotik at the time was limited to 2GB of RAM on x86 hardware) I ended up at PfSense.
PfSense was installed on the same hardware, a HP ProLiant ML110 G5 with 8GB RAM, a Core2Quad processor and 12 GigE Network cards&hellip; And, on PfSense, things were good&hellip; Performance was stable, load balancing worked as expected, I could set some traffic to go over certain links, etc. all was good&hellip; But I lacked IPv6&hellip; Plus, the HP used a LOT of power&hellip;
The current instalment of my network uses a Ubiquiti Networks Edge Router POE. To show the difference in power, check out the graphs from my Ubnt MPower device. ProLiant first, EdgeRouter second:
Plus, the EdgeRouter does not produce as much heat, and its a LOT smaller that the PowerEdge! It does all the same things I could get PfSense to do, in a lot smaller package (I could, in theory, get a smaller box for PfSense).
So, where does that leave us? Well, I now have 720Mbit/s down and 72Mbit/s up, if I can do multiple threads for uploading&hellip; But what if I don&rsquo;t? What&rsquo;s next? Well, in the second post, I will explain what I have been trying to do in resent weeks, and what I can do now&hellip;

So, after some messing, tweaking, and thinking, I have made some progress with the home lab&hellip; or at least broken some stuff&hellip; I mentioned previously that i had a Ubiqititi networks EdgeRouter POE in the home lab. Originally, the plan was to use a Virtual PFSense box for my core router&hellip; Given the power usage of the current PfSense Box (I have 2 MPower Pro&rsquo;s watching power in the lab) I am now thinking of moving to just the EdgeRouter for, well, edge routing&hellip; below is the usage of the ProLiant for the last 12 hours or so:
for the same period, here is the usage for the Edge Router:
I am also setting up a DMZ for front facing services, and then a LAN for inside facing machines. There will be a firewall (currently thinking Sophos UTM or similar) between the DMZ and the network. Some machines will be able to access the DMZ, and there may be machines allowed into the LAN, but only some things&hellip; not even sure if that would be done&hellip;
I also need to work out the VLAN side of things. I have currently though of the following VLAN setup:
